    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-18T09:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-18T09:29:00-05:00" n="407"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d407">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/1322</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_FDR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Francis</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vologda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-18T17:00:00+02:31">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 18, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 20, 12.06 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>17. Have telegraphed Tokyo and Peking requesting keep me advised developments
                    especially movements Japanese, Chinese troops. If division each American and
                    Chinese troops could enter Russia with Japanese, think opposition to latter be
                    minimized thereby.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_TRC1">Tredwell</persName>, whom I sent to Petrograd, wires
                    it is believed that city be controlled by German commission supported by army
                    within a week; that next move will be on Moscow, and peace will be brief.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_TRC1">Tredwell</persName> telegraphs, <persName
                        corresp="#p_HT1">Haynes</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_SEG1"
                        >Sisson</persName> with other Americans left Helsingfors 12th for
                    Björneborg, Finnish port.</p>
                <p>I gave Moscow and Petrograd press declaration that America does not recognize
                    separate peace, but considers herself still ally of Russian people against
                    common enemy. Told mayor of it, and asked if would be less welcome thereby; he
                    replied promptly would not.</p>
                <p>Mayor, commissaire, chairmen Duma and local Soviet, and five other officials
                    dining at local Embassy 19th instant.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_FDR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Francis</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
